Hello everyone,
Brigade 55 has left Kfar Aza and continues to its next missions.
Responsibility has been transferred to a battalion from Brigade 5 under command of CENSORED
The three days in which we defended, fought and collected the remains of Kfar Aza's heroes are deeply engraved in Brigade 55's memory alongside the battles of Ammunition Hill, the liberation of the Western Wall and crossing the Canal.
With a salute and endless respect to the heroes of Kfar Aza, I'll end with a quote from Dayan's famous speech at Roi Rotberg's grave:
'How can we close our eyes and refuse to look straight at our fate, to see the destiny of our generation in all its cruelty? Have we forgotten that this group of youngsters, sitting in Nachal Oz [and in Kfar Aza], carries on its shoulders the heavy gates of Gaza - gates behind which hundreds of thousands of eyes and hands are crowded, praying for our weakness to come, so they can tear us to pieces - have we forgotten this? We know that in order for the hope to destroy us to die, we must be, morning and evening, armed and ready.'
We are a generation of settlement, and without the steel helmet and cannon muzzle we cannot plant a tree or build a house. Our children will not have lives if we do not dig shelters, and without barbed wire and machine guns we cannot pave a road or drill for water. The millions of Jews who were destroyed without having a country look upon us from the ashes of Jewish history and command us to settle and establish a land for our people. But beyond the border furrow surges a sea of hatred and vengeful desires, waiting for the day when tranquility dulls our vigilance, for the day when we listen to the ambassadors of malicious hypocrisy calling us to lay down our arms. Roi's blood cries out to us from his torn body. Though we have sworn a thousand times that our blood shall not be spilled in vain - yesterday we were tempted again, we listened and believed. We will settle our account with ourselves today. Let us not shrink from seeing the hatred that accompanies and fills the lives of hundreds of thousands of Arabs who sit around us and wait for the moment when their hand can reach our blood. Let us not avert our eyes lest our hand weaken. This is the fate of our generation. This is our life's choice - to be prepared and armed, strong and tough, or else the sword shall fall from our fist and our lives will be cut short.'
May the memory of Kfar Aza's heroes and martyrs be blessed. Their memory and bravery are preserved in our hearts forever
